<h2 id="org4eb4447">Great read: Is Classical Liberalism for Losers</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org4eb4447">
<p>
<a href="https://www.thefp.com/p/tyler-cowen-is-classical-liberalism-for-losers">https://www.thefp.com/p/tyler-cowen-is-classical-liberalism-for-losers</a>
</p>

<p>
Classical liberals can be on the center right or the center
left. They can as easily be registered Republicans as registered
Democrats. What they share is a philosophy that believes in strong
limits on state power; a reliance on democratic procedures and
constitutional constraints; a belief in capitalism and innovation as
the wellsprings of progress; and strong support for toleration and
free speech. Classical liberalism also implies that the state should
be relatively neutral across competing cultural values, and that one
should not presuppose that one’s own political rule will always be so
wonderful. Classical liberalism necessitates a good dose of humility
for this reason.
</p>

<p>
The classical liberal, in contrast, expresses the more complicated
message. It goes something like: “less government rule and extend
progress, while respecting due process, the rule of law, and
compromise!”
</p>
